What is Task Scheduler?

The Task Scheduler service allows you to perform automated tasks on a chosen computer. With this service, you can schedule any program or document to run at a time that is convenient for you.

When a specific event occurs.

It monitors the time or event criteria you choose and then executes the task when those criteria are met.

It is implemented and was first introduced in the Microsoft Plus for Windows 95 as System Agent.

Task scheduler is automatically installed on Windows OS, and is started each time the operating system is started. It can run through the Task scheduler graphical user interface (GUI) or by using command line.

By default, you must be a member of the Administrators, Backup operators, or server operators group on the local computer to view, add, edit, or delete scheduled tasks, or to disable, pause, or restart the Task Scheduler service.

Function of Task Scheduler

Schedule a task to run daily, weekly, monthly, or at certain times. (such as system startup).

Change the scheduler for a task.

Stop a scheduled task.

Customize how a task runs at a scheduled time.

Components of Task Scheduler

The Task Scheduler service is comprised of the following components:

Mstask.dll: Task scheduler interface DLL

Mstask.exe: Task scheduler engine (Windows 2000 only).

Schedsvc.dll: Task scheduler Engine (Windows XP 2003)

Mstinit.exe: Task scheduler help

Components of a Task

Triggers: Task scheduler uses event or time based triggers to know when to start a task. Every task can specify one or more triggers to start the task.

Actions: These are the actions, the actual work, that is performed by the task. Every task can specify oneor more actions to complete work.

Principals: Principals define the security context in which the task is run. For eg, a principal might define a specific user or user group that can run the task.

Settings: These are the settings that the Task Scheduler uses to run the task with respect to conditions that are external to the task itself.

Note: By default, a task will be stopped 72 hours after it starts to run. You can change this by changing the Execution Time Limit setting.

Registration Information: This is administrative information that is gathered when the task is registered. Example: the author of the task, the date when the task registered, XML description of the task.

Data: This is additional documentation about the task that is supplied by the author of the task.

Types of Triggers

Time-based Triggers: Time-based triggers start tasks at specified times. This includes starting the task once at a specific time or starting the task multiple times on a daily, weekly, monthly or monthly day of week schedule.

Event-based Triggers: It starts a task in response to certain system events.

